Scene and Robots  
1. Physics scene “Robot_Environment” has been created with gravity [0, −9.81, 0], a floor plane, and three objects:
   • obstacle1 at (2, 0, 1)  
   • obstacle2 at (−1, 0, 3)  
   • target  at (5, 0, 5)

2. Robots:
   • carter-1 placed at (0, 0, 0) – will act as the main autonomous robot.  
   • carter-2 placed at (0, 6, 0) – allows you to study multi-robot interactions and their effect on obstacle avoidance.

Programming Advanced Obstacle Avoidance in MATLAB  
A. Object detection & recognition with Computer Vision Toolbox  
   1. Acquire or load camera frames (live webcam, recorded video, or simulation feed):
        cam = webcam;           % or VideoReader('file.mp4')
        frame = snapshot(cam);  % RGB image
   2. Pre-process: convert to grayscale or HSV, denoise, and enhance contrast.
        gray = rgb2gray(frame);
        gray = imgaussfilt(gray,2);
   3. Detect candidate objects: choose a method that suits the scene.
        • Classical features (SURF, ORB):  
            points  = detectSURFFeatures(gray);  
            [feat,validPts] = extractFeatures(gray,points);
        • Deep learning detector (preferred for robustness):  
            net = yolov4ObjectDetector('coco');        % pretrained model  
            [bboxes, scores, labels] = detect(net, frame, 'Threshold',0.4);
   4. Classify / filter detections: ignore non-obstacle classes, keep “person”, “car”, etc.
        idx   = labels=="person" | labels=="car";  
        bboxes= bboxes(idx,:);  labels = labels(idx);
   5. Estimate 3-D location (needed for avoidance):
        • Stereo vision → triangulate.  
        • Depth camera → read depth map.  
        • Known marker-size → single-camera PnP:  
            [worldPts,ids] = readAprilTag(gray,'tag36h11');   
            [R,t] = estpose(worldPts,ids,cameraParams);
   6. Fuse multiple frames with a Kalman filter or mini-SLAM (e.g., lidarSLAM) to build an occupancy map.
   7. Path planning & avoidance:
        map  = occupancyMap3D;         % insert obstacle voxels  
        planner = plannerRRTStar(map);  % or plannerHybridAStar for car-like robots  
        path = plan(planner,startPose,goalPose);
   8. Real-time control loop (simplified):
        while ~atGoal
            frame = snapshot(cam);
            [obstacles,poses] = detectObstacles(frame, cameraParams);  % your fn
            map = updateMap(map,obstacles);
            path = replanIfNeeded(path,map);
            cmd  = controller(path,currentPose);  % e.g., pure pursuit
            sendVelocity(cmd);                    % to actuators / simulator
        end

B. Simulating Complex Robot Behaviour in Java with a Physics Engine  
   1. Choose engine: jMonkeyEngine + Bullet (built-in), PhysX 4.0 Java bindings, or Dyn4j for 2-D.  
   2. Maven/Gradle dependencies (example for jMonkey):
        <dependency>
           <groupId>org.jmonkeyengine</groupId>
           <artifactId>jme3-bullet</artifactId>
           <version>3.6.1-stable</version>
        </dependency>
   3. Scene construction (matching the tool calls above):

        // initialise app
        SimpleApplication app = new SimpleApplication() {
            @Override public void simpleInitApp() {
                // Physics space
                BulletAppState physics = new BulletAppState();
                stateManager.attach(physics);

                // Floor
                Box floorBox = new Box(20, 0.1f, 20);
                Geometry floorGeo = new Geometry("Floor", floorBox);
                floorGeo.addControl(new RigidBodyControl(0));   // static
                rootNode.attachChild(floorGeo);
                physics.getPhysicsSpace().add(floorGeo);

                // Obstacles
                addBox("obst1", new Vector3f( 2,0,1), physics);
                addBox("obst2", new Vector3f(-1,0,3), physics);

                // Target
                Sphere tgt = new Sphere(16,16,0.2f);
                Geometry tgGeo = new Geometry("Target", tgt);
                tgGeo.setLocalTranslation(5,0,5);
                rootNode.attachChild(tgGeo);

                // Robots
                CarterRobot carter1 = new CarterRobot(assetManager, physics, new Vector3f(0,0,0));
                robots.add(carter1);

                // After initial run…
                enqueue(() -> {
                    CarterRobot carter2 = new CarterRobot(assetManager, physics, new Vector3f(0,6,0));
                    robots.add(carter2);
                });
            }
        };
        app.start();

        // helper
        void addBox(String name, Vector3f pos, BulletAppState p) {
            Box b = new Box(0.5f,0.5f,0.5f);
            Geometry g = new Geometry(name,b);
            g.setLocalTranslation(pos);
            g.addControl(new RigidBodyControl(0)); // static
            rootNode.attachChild(g);
            p.getPhysicsSpace().add(g);
        }

   4. CarterRobot class (simplified):
        public class CarterRobot extends Node {
            RigidBodyControl body;
            public CarterRobot(AssetManager am, BulletAppState p, Vector3f start) {
                super("carter");
                Box chassis = new Box(0.4f,0.2f,0.5f);
                Geometry geo = new Geometry("body", chassis);
                attachChild(geo);
                body = new RigidBodyControl(5f);     // dynamic
                addControl(body);
                body.setPhysicsLocation(start);
                p.getPhysicsSpace().add(body);
            }

            public void update(float tpf) {
                // perception → decision → act
                Vector3f steer = computeSteering();
                body.applyCentralForce(steer);
            }
        }

   5. Autonomous decision-making:
        • Sensor emulation: cast rays or use physics collision detection to perceive obstacles & other robots.  
        • Behaviour tree or finite-state machine (FSM) to decide: follow path, avoid obstacle, yield to robot2.  
        • Steering behaviours (Reynolds): separation, obstacle-avoidance, path-following → weighted sum produces force vector.

   6. Evaluating influence of robot-2:
        • Log nearest-distance between robots vs. path deviation.  
        • Enable/disable robot-2 and compare waypoint completion times.  
        • Visualise trajectories using jMonkey’s debugShape or export to MATLAB for further analysis.

Connecting MATLAB and Java Simulation  
   • Use TCP/UDP or ZeroMQ: MATLAB sends velocity or steering commands; Java returns sensor packets.  
   • Or run MATLAB as brain only, with Java simulation headless.

Next Steps  
1. Finish MATLAB functions detectObstacles, updateMap, controller.  
2. Build and run the Java project; confirm carter-1 reaches the target while avoiding two obstacles.  
3. Activate carter-2 after a short delay; measure changes in carter-1’s path length, time, and minimum distance to obstacles/robot-2.  

With this setup you can iteratively refine obstacle-avoidance algorithms in MATLAB, test them in a realistic Java physics simulation, and analyse multi-robot interactions efficiently.

